{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17499354","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17499354"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T09:58:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T09:58:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1489"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1489","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1489"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.45,0.03,0.45,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1489"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47637"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1489","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1489"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1489"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32363"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"20"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"813"},{"type":"tags","id":"1215"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6013"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6441"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12414"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47637","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/47637"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 66-year-old man presents to his General Practice clinic for a routine health check. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. During the examination, the doctor observes the following changes in the patient\u0027s left hand (Image). The contracture is non-painful and unable to be straightened.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying pathological process?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Chronic tenosynovitis","Flexor tendon sheath contracture","Ulnar claw","Fibrosis of the palmar fascia","Volar ganglion cyst"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis image shows a classic presentation of Dupuytren\u0027s contracture, which is caused by \u003Cstrong\u003Efibrosis of the palmar fascia\u003C/strong\u003E. Dupuytren\u0027s contracture is an example of myofibroblastic disease where proliferation of myofibroblasts and Type III collagen results in the transformation of fascial bands into painless cords that pull on the digits (most commonly 4th and 5th digits) to form flexion contractures. These contractures commonly have a genetic origin and are also associated with diabetes, seizures, smoking, alcoholism, and vascular disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronic tenosynovitis\u003C/strong\u003E is a painful condition resulting from the inflammation of a tendon sheath. Pain or restricted movement is generally the presenting complaint, which is not consistent with the painless contracture described in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlexor tendon sheath contracture\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as trigger finger, is caused by repetitive friction between the flexor tendon and its sheath. It is a pathology of the tendons and generally causes pain and a locking of movement rather than presenting purely as a contracture. Additionally, these contractures can be straightened using the other hand or by a third party, unlike Dupuytren\u0027s contractures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUlnar claw\u003C/strong\u003E is a deformity resulting from ulnar nerve palsy, characterized by hyperextension of the metacarpophalangeal joints and flexion of the interphalangeal joints of the 4th and 5th fingers. This presentation differs from the image shown, which depicts a classic Dupuytren\u0027s contracture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVolar ganglion cyst\u003C/strong\u003E is a benign soft tissue tumor that typically presents as a visible or palpable mass on the volar aspect of the wrist or fingers. It would not cause the contracture seen in this image and is generally painless unless it compresses nearby nerves.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Dupuytren\u0027s contracture is characterized by fibrosis of the palmar fascia, resulting in flexion contractures of the digits, most commonly affecting the 4th and 5th fingers.","Dupuytren\u0027s contracture is associated with genetic factors, diabetes, seizures, smoking, alcoholism, and vascular disease."],"references":["Walthall J, Anand P, Rehman UH. Dupuytren Contracture. [Updated 2022 Apr 30]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK526074/","Yang K, Gehring M, Bou Zein Eddine S, Hettinger P. Association between Stenosing Tenosynovitis and Dupuytren\u0027s Contracture in the Hand. Plast Reconstr Surg Glob Open. 2019 Jan 11;7(1):e2088. doi: 10.1097/GOX.0000000000002088. PMID: 30859045; PMCID: PMC6382223.","Mirza TM, Taqi M. Volkmann Contracture. [Updated 2022 May 15]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK557754/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32363"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1489"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"16091"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"16091","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/16091"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/cd3fc525-c8d2-4bde-bbb7-6aed53e6ac3c.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/cd3fc525-c8d2-4bde-bbb7-6aed53e6ac3c.jpg","isProcessed":